snippet.textDisplay: 😊 I just started taking some cooking classes, and one of the ones I took was a knife skills class. I can cook, but with the things I learned from these classes has changed the game and I can do more with less more efficiently. The only things I'll say is the you would curl your knuckles in to prevent accidentally cutting yourself and you push the knife forward and dont saw like you are cutting wood. You push the knife away from you into the food item and then it cuts from there.  Would would also want to make what you are cutting a little flat on one side so that It is more stable when cutting it. Thank you for showing everyone that your can always learn something new 😊👍
snippet.textOriginal: 😊 I just started taking some cooking classes, and one of the ones I took was a knife skills class. snippet.textDisplay: I heard a long time ago I can’t remember where, that apparently whatever substance that gets released by the onion once you cut it that makes you cry, is attracted to moist. And since our eyes are the most moist part of the external part of our bodies, that’s where that substance ends up going to. And since our eyes are sensitive to it, they start burning and producing tears. So to avoid that, you should get your hands and wrists wet so that when you cut an onion, that substance ends up going to your hands and wrists instead of your eyes. I don’t know if that’s true but I’ve been doing it for years now and it always works. Could be just a placebo effect. Maybe you guys could test out this theory 😬
